INSERT INTO `resumen` VALUES (148,'The Aztec Calendar Stone (Piedra del Sol), a large, unfinished altar discovered in 1790, is a key Mexica artifact.  Its intricate carvings depict Xiuhtecuhtli, the fire god, emerging from the earth, holding hearts and a sacrificial knife.  Surrounding him are the four previous suns and the twenty day signs, all framed by fire serpents.  Despite a fracture, it likely served as a gladiatorial sacrifice platform during the Tlacaxipehualiztli ceremony.\n',1,24),(149,'Mexica cosmology envisioned a vertically structured universe with thirteen celestial layers above and nine underworld layers below the earthly plane, *tlaticpac*.  The highest celestial layer, Omeyocan, housed the creator gods.  The underworld culminated in Mictlan, ruled by Mictlantecuhtli and Mictecacíhuatl. This vertical structure intersected with a four-directional model, each cardinal point representing a significant region: east (red, birth, Xochipilli); west (white, women, Cihuateteo); north (black, death, Mixcoatl); south (blue, Huitzilopochtli).  The center, where these directions converged, was considered sacred and the ideal location for capitals, ruled by Xipe Totec.\n',11,24),(150,'Mexica cosmology viewed the universe as a vertical structure with thirteen celestial layers culminating in Omeyocan, home of the creator gods, and nine underworld levels ending in Mictlan.  Simultaneously, it was a four-directional system, each cardinal point representing a significant region: east (red, birth), west (white, women), north (black, death), and south (blue, Huitzilopochtli\'s domain).  The center, Xjuhtecuhtli\'s realm, was considered the intersection of these cosmic forces, where all indigenous capitals were believed to be situated.\n',11,24),(151,'Pre-Hispanic cosmology viewed the sun as vital, its presence and destruction mirroring life\'s instability.  Creation myths detail five suns, each representing an era ruled by different deities and elemental forces (earth, wind, fire, water).  Each sun\'s destruction stemmed from its inherent nature.  The fifth sun, and current one, was created through the self-sacrifice of Nanahuatzin and Tecuciztécatl, becoming the sun and moon.  Human sacrifice was seen as necessary to maintain the sun\'s power, providing life-giving light and heat essential for growth and existence.\n',8,24),(152,'Pre-Hispanic Mexico boasted a sophisticated herbal medicine tradition, honed over centuries.  The Codex Libellus de Medicinalibus Indorum Herbis showcases the extensive knowledge of native healers, who utilized plants, animals, minerals, and even obsidian in treatments.  The goddess Tzapotlatena, revered for her discovery of resin\'s medicinal properties, exemplifies the importance of this knowledge system.  This rich pharmacopoeia, documented by figures like Martín de la Cruz and Bernardino de Sahagún, predates the Spanish conquest.\n',14,24),(153,'Long before the Spanish arrived, the people of the Mexico-Tenochtitlán region possessed a sophisticated herbal medicine tradition.  Their knowledge, documented in works like the Libellus de Medicinalibus Indorum Herbis, showcased a vast array of medicinal plants and their uses.  This expertise extended beyond plants, incorporating animals, minerals, and even obsidian into treatments.  The goddess Tzapotlatena, deified for her discovery of resin\'s medicinal properties, exemplifies the reverence for healing knowledge within their culture.\n',14,24),(154,'Pre-Hispanic Mexico boasted a sophisticated herbal medicine tradition, honed over centuries.  The Codex Libellus de Medicinalibus Indorum Herbis showcases the extensive knowledge of native healers, utilizing plants, animals, minerals, and even obsidian for treatments.  The goddess Tzapotlatena exemplifies this expertise, deified for her discovery of resin\'s medicinal properties.  This rich pharmacopoeia, documented by figures like Martín de la Cruz and Bernardino de Sahagún, highlights the advanced medical understanding of the Mexica civilization.\n',14,24),(155,'Every 52 years, the Mexica celebrated Xiumolpillia.  They burned bundles of 52 sticks, symbolizing the end of a cycle.  Homes were darkened, a sacrifice occurred on Cerro de la Estrella, and a new fire ignited, beginning a new 52-year period.  Stone carvings depicting the ritual, dated \"2 Cane,\" were buried in tombs marked with skulls and bones, representing the cyclical nature of life and death.\n',16,24),(156,'Every 52 years, the Mexica celebrated Xiumolpillia.  This involved burning bundles of 52 sticks, symbolizing the end of a cycle.  All fires were extinguished, a sacrifice made, and a new fire kindled, representing rebirth.  Stone carvings commemorating the event (dated \"2 Cane\") were buried in sacred tombs, marked with skulls and bones, signifying the cyclical nature of life and death.\n',16,24),(157,'Every 52 years, the Mexica celebrated Xiumolpillia.  This involved burning bundles of 52 sticks, symbolizing the end of a cycle.  All fires were extinguished, a sacrifice made, and a new fire lit from the sacrifice on Cerro de la Estrella, beginning a new 52-year period.  Stone carvings marking the \"2 Cane\" year were created and buried in tombs decorated with skulls and bones, representing the cyclical nature of life and death.\n',16,24),(158,'Every 52 years, the Mexica celebrated Xiumolpillia.  This involved burning bundles of 52 sticks, symbolizing the end of a cycle.  Homes were extinguished, a sacrifice made, and a new fire ignited on Cerro de la Estrella, starting a new 52-year period.  Stone carvings depicting the \"2 Cane\" date and the stick bundles were buried in tombs marked with skulls and bones, representing the cyclical nature of life and death.\n',16,24);
